welcome to the demo for swiftpick.nvim!

swiftpick is a file picker that makes it trivial
to work on multiple files at the same time.

if you know harpoon, it's very similar,
but with some adjustments that provide a better UX

each working directory has its own file-switching context.
or, we can pick from a global context (available from any dir)

here's some examples.

1.  opening the swiftpick window

    <leader>h

with the window open, we can perform any of the following actions:

2.  adding the current file (swiftpick-demo) to swiftpick

    a

3.  switch files
       note that the picker window highlights shows the keybind
       and index for the corresponding file.

    <index | entry keybind>     (e.g. h or 1, j or 3 )

    first we'll switch slowly from top-to-bottom so you can follow along,
    then we'll gradually speed up to show it's speed.

5.  removing the current file from swiftpick

    r

6.  inserting the current file at a specific entry
       note that the other entries shift down to accomodate
       its new position.

    A then <index | entry keybind>   (e.g. Ah, A3)

7.  similarly, we can remove entries at specific keybinds

    R then <index | entry keybind>   (e.g. Rh, R3)

8.  toggle between relative and absolute path display:

    t

9.  toggle between local and global context

    T

10. edit the picker like any other neovim buffer
       this allows us to pick an entry by highlighted line,
       swap entries around, or remove/edit them. 

    e

we can set also do much more, like setup custom keybinds that,
    e.g. open the picker in global context mode
         or add all files in the current cwd

swiftpick is awesome. try it today!
